[{"id":"VR618518","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a box sliding to the right on a horizontal surface. Point P divides the horizontal surface into two regions, and the box is in the region to the left of point P. A horizontal tension F sub T is exerted on the box and points to the right.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR618518.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A constant, horizontal tension <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub T\"><math alttext=\"F sub T\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mtext>T</mtext></msub></math></span></span> is exerted on a box as it slides to the right across a rough, horizontal surface, as shown in the figure. In the region to the left of Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>, the magnitude of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub T\"><math alttext=\"F sub T\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mtext>T</mtext></msub></math></span></span> is equal to the magnitude of the force of kinetic friction between the box and the surface. After the box reaches Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>, friction between the box and the surface becomes negligible and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub T\"><math alttext=\"F sub T\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mtext>T</mtext></msub></math></span></span> remains constant. Consider the horizontal velocity of the box when it is on the surface before Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span> and after Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>. Which statements below correctly describe and justify the motion of the box in the two regions?</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup align:left cols:3 colsep:0 frame:none rowsep:0\"><col class=\"colspec colname:col1 colnum:1 colsep:1\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col2 colnum:2 colwidth:220\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col3 colnum:3 colwidth:220\"/><thead class=\"thead\"><tr class=\"row rowsep:1\"><th class=\"entry colname:col1\"></th><th class=\"entry colname:col2\">Before <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span></th><th class=\"entry colname:col3\">After <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span></th></tr></thead><tbody class=\"tbody valign:middle\"><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">A</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Constant velocity, because the horizontal forces are balanced.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Increasing velocity, because the horizontal forces are now unbalanced.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">B</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Constant velocity, because the horizontal forces are balanced.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Constant velocity because the object does not have any force of friction exerted on it to reduce its velocity.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">C</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Decreasing velocity because the tension is not greater than the force of kinetic friction.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Increasing velocity because the horizontal forces are now unbalanced.</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">D</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Decreasing velocity because the tension is not greater than the force of kinetic friction.</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Constant velocity, because the object does not have any force of friction exerted on it to reduce its velocity.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR618518_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">A</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">B</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">C</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">D</p>"],"answer":0}]